The paper deals with the problem of inferring missing information diffusion histories in social networks, which is a topic that falls under the intersection of several sub-fields in computer science. The most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), which specifically deals with the analysis and modeling of social networks and information diffusion. The paper also involves the use of tensor decomposition techniques, which are commonly used in the sub-category of cs.SD (Sound and Music Computing). Additionally, the paper involves the use of machine learning techniques to infer the missing information, which falls under the sub-categories of cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Finally, the paper involves the analysis of real-world datasets, which falls under the sub-category of cs.SOC (Computational Social Science).
